did.abstract: The New York Building Congress (NYBC) is an association that brings together employers, labor unions, government agencies, engineers, architects, financiers, suppliers, and others engaged in the construction industry in New York City. Founded in 1921, it now has ca. 400 affiliated organizations, with a combined membership of over 250,000 skilled workers and professionals. The Congress engages in educational and lobbying activity, hosts public programs, and disseminates information on issues of concern to the industry. The collection consists of black and white and color photographs (some with negatives) and slides documenting personnel, activities and special events of the Congress, with portraits of noted political figures and other awardees and guests at Congress events. Also included are a small number of images of construction sites and office interiors.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The collection is comprised of the photographs, contact sheets, and negatives of the New York Building Congress. These photographs document administrative meetings of the NYBC and awards dinners, luncheons, and other social events hosted by the Congress, as well as some industry events. Included are portraits of key individuals in the New York City building industry and political establishment. Events such as industry recognition dinners, golf outings, and the Christmas show "Fun and Frolic" are particularly well represented in the collection. “Fun and Frolic” was a comedy revue featuring political satire and musical performances held annually at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel. Though the shows were written and directed by professionals, all roles (both male and female) were played by volunteer, male members of the NYBC. First held in 1938, the “Fun and Frolic” show was discontinued during the late 1980s.

The majority of photographic prints in the collection are black and white 8 x 10 prints; also included are color prints in a variety of sizes, including 4" x 6" and 3" x 4". Photographs and matching negatives are placed in the same folder, and the presence of negatives is noted in the finding aid. There are a limited number of contact sheets, also indicated in the finding aid. Additionally, this collection includes approximately 500 stereo slides dating from 1952 and 1953.
Series I: Meetings, 1947-1999, consists of photographs of administrative meetings, including those of the Board of Directors and Council of Presidents, as well as a variety of committees.

Series II: Events, 1944-2008, contains photographs of annual industry and social events, such as the Leadership Awards Luncheon, Fun and Frolic, the Industry Recognition Dinner, and golf outings. Also included are special receptions and forums with prominent visiting speakers.

Series III: Portraits, 1936-1988, includes portraits of key individuals in the building industry and political establishment in New York City. Many of these were acquired for use in NYBC publications, especially for publicity on featured speakers at Congress events.
Series IV: Site Photographs, 1948-1974, contains a small number of photographs of construction sites and office environments.

Series V: Other Formats and Oversize, 1943-1988, contains stereo slides produced by the NYBC in 1952 and 1953. The approximately 500 stereo slides document meetings, the annual "Fun and Frolic" (1952 and 1953), and various social outings. Also included in this series are a small number of oversize items and the rolled photographs. Note that approximately 15 tightly rolled photographs, indicated as restricted in the finding aid, are not immediately available for reference use. Please consult Tamiment staff regarding access to these materials.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The New York Building Congress (NYBC) is an association that brings together employers, labor unions and federations, government agencies, engineers, architects, financiers, suppliers, and others engaged in the construction industry in New York City. Founded in 1921, it now has ca. 400 affiliated organizations, with a combined membership of over 250,000 skilled workers and professionals. The Congress engages in educational and lobbying activity, hosts public programs, and disseminates information on issues of concern to the industry.

Shortly after the First World War, elements of the American building industry attempted to organize a national building congress. Although the planned national organization was never very active, the impulse was continued by city-wide groups. In New York City, the 47-member NYBC was organized in early 1921. Originally, membership was limited to organizations (labor unions, businesses, government agencies, etc.), but it was soon opened to individuals, and its early presidents were noted architects. On this broad basis, NYBC united labor and employers, as well as members of multiple professions involved in the building industry. One of the NYBC's key roles in its early years was to mediate between labor and management.

The NYBC issued a code of ethics for the building industry during its inaugural year, and remained actively involved in setting industry standards. The organization concerned itself with specific building practices; it commissioned research, published reports, lobbied, and spoke out on legislation and regulations pertaining to the industry. The NYBC took a leading role in the revision of the New York City Building Code in the 1960s and also lobbied on more general issues, such as the New York City Charter revision of the late 1980s.

The NYBC has been led in recent decades by Louis Coletti (1986-1994) and then by Richard T. Anderson (1994-present). During this time, the Congress has frequently addressed legislative, regulatory issue, urban developement, and political issues crucial to the industry. A recent Congress intiative was the establishment of the New York Building Foundation (NYBF), which undertakes industry research and philanthropic activities.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material at the Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives
relatedmaterial.p: The Tamiment Library holds a number of periodicals published by NYBC, including the Building Congress News, Metrobuild, and Edifice

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p:
Published citations should take the following form:
Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 70 Washington Square South New York, NY 10012 New York University Libraries.

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: The New York Building Congress collection was donated to the Tamiment Library in 1999, through an agreement with Richard T. Anderson, President of the Congress. Additional material was donated in 2009 and 2011.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: A limited number of restricted materials (approximately 15 rolled photographs) are noted in the container list. Please consult Tamiment staff for access to these materials.
